node.text:
This morning, I had the honor of speaking at the Downtown Mobile Alliance Mayor’s Breakfast about some of the plans we have in the works for the downtown area.

From the restoration of Bienville Square to the recently announced plans to activate the riverfront, Broad Street revitalization, Roll Mobile, and Artwalk to CPSI moving their headquarters to Conception - Downtown is thriving.

node.text:
Calagaz Printing, a Mobile print shop, has switched from printing menus to manufacturing face shields for health care workers.

With business down because of #COVID19, one of their team members came up with this wild idea, to produce face shields. Turns out they can not only do it, but they can produce a bunch, quickly!

So, in less than a week, they created a prototype, met with hospitals, ordered materials and today they will deliver the first 5,000 to Mobile’s four hospitals. Next week they plan to ramp up and produce 5,000/day. 
Kudos to Calagaz for thinking outside the box and working hard to make this happen. As a local, family-owned business, they are helping us turn the tide in the fight against Coronavirus and keeping their employees working, too.

node.text: We had a fantastic lunch yesterday at Bay Barbeque as we closed out Small Business Week in the City of Mobile. Pitmaster Arthur Green’s barbequing career started off as a hobby — cooking for family and friends and taking a few catering orders here and there. After he finished in the Top 15 at the Memphis in May barbeque contest, he started thinking seriously about setting up his own restaurant. Three years later you can come try Arthur’s award-winning ribs and brisket for yourself in the heart of midtown Mobile.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Sandy Stimpson on September 17, 2021.

node.text: As part of our Small Business Week visits, we stopped by Dog Days Barkery yesterday afternoon to talk with owner Carra Smith about the unique business she started with her mother and father. Their mission is to provide higher-quality food products for Mobile’s pets. Every day, the Dog Days team is making freshly baked food and treats for dogs and cats with human-grade ingredients, and they look good enough to eat. We talked about the role small businesses play in the community and how the City can support them. We know that all our small businesses play a part in making Mobile a great place to live.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Sandy Stimpson on September 16, 2021. May be an image of 2 people, people standing and indoor.

node.text: As part of Small Business Week, I took the opportunity this afternoon to stop by Amber Ivey Fine Art. We had a great visit at her studio, and talked about how her business got started and has evolved over the last eight years. We also talked about the importance of local art in our community. Amber said the success of each local small business is a success for Mobile, and I couldn't agree more.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Sandy Stimpson on September 14, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and indoor.

node.text:
I started my week off with a cup of tea at Maple Street Biscuit Company. Some of my staff and I stopped in to kick off National Small Business Week. For more than 50 years, the Small Business Administration has celebrated Small Business Week to recognize and celebrate the critical contributions of America’s entrepreneurs and small business owners. We plan to visit other small businesses throughout Mobile this week to highlight their contributions to the City and to meet with the owners. 

According to SBA, more than half of Americans either own or work for a small business, and they create nearly two out of every three new jobs in the U.S. each year. We are blessed in Mobile to have so many small businesses offering wonderful products, services, and experiences. Make sure that you’re supporting them every week, but especially this week as we celebrate what they mean to our community.

node.text: Finally, it was my honor yesterday to join first responders from the City of Mobile during a ceremony at Mobile Memorial Gardens commemorating the 20th anniversary of the 9-11 attacks on the United States. Public Safety Director Lawrence Battiste gave the memorial message, remembering the heroism and sacrifice of all who lost their lives that day. Thirty firefighters from local departments who passed away in 2020 and 2021 were also recognized at the ceremony by Mobile Fire-Rescue Chief Jeremy Lami. We thank those men for their years of service protecting our communities and our citizens.

node.text:
During this week’s City Council meeting, we were able to recognize September as National Recovery Month in the City of Mobile. This annual event aims to educate the public about how substance use and mental health services can help individuals struggling with addiction and their families to live healthy and rewarding lives. 

Each year, National Recovery Month also celebrates the millions of people in recovery from challenges with mental health and substance abuse that impact so many in our community. On Tuesday, I was honored to join representatives from the Drug Education Council, People Engaging in Recovery and Faces and Voices of Recovery (FAVOR) in asking Mobilians and all residents of Alabama to participate in National Recovery Month. Mental illness and substance use touch all our lives, but we can help achieve long term recovery through advocacy, education and access to resources.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Sandy Stimpson on September 08, 2021. May be an image of 5 people and people standing.

node.text:
It is National Suicide Prevention Week, and yesterday I joined the Mobile City Council in bringing attention to this important cause in the City of Mobile. We know that Suicide remains the 10th leading cause of death in the United States and the 2nd leading cause of death among individuals between the ages of 10 to 34, and we also know that over 90 percent of the people who die by suicide have a diagnosable, treatable mental health condition that is all too often unrecognized or undiagnosed.

During yesterday's City Council meeting we were joined by local representatives from the American Foundation for Suicide Prevention and other individuals who have been personally impacted by suicide to remind those struggling that there is always a way out of the darkness. There is always hope. If you or someone you know is struggling, the National Suicide Prevention Hotline is (800) 273-8255.

node.text:
it was my pleasure to join Mobile City Council President Levon Manzie and Public Works Director Jim DeLapp to unveil a sign announcing the upcoming Texas Street project. This will be a $6 million investment from the City, Mobile County and the Mobile Area Water and Sewer Service and is the direct result of Councilman Manzie’s consistent efforts to find the funding for this project.

Those who travel Texas Street every day know this project is long overdue, but this won't just put a new layer of asphalt over an old problem. This is a complete rebuild from the ground up that will run for nine blocks between Broad Street and Ann Street. In addition to the new roadways, curbs, gutters and sidewalks, it will also include much needed upgrades to the stormwater system as well as the gas, water and sewer lines underground.

node.text:
August 30, 2021 

 Mayor Sandy Stimpson rescinds state of emergency, City offices open Tuesday 

 Mobile, Ala. – At noon today Mayor Sandy Stimpson rescinded the order declaring a state of emergency effective at 6:00 pm, August 30th. In accordance, City of Mobile offices will be open, and all employees will return for normal business hours on Tuesday, August 31st.

“Mobile has been fortunate to avoid the devastating impacts of Hurricane Ida that were felt to the West, but City crews are continuing to evaluate minor reports of storm damage and flash flooding in low-lying areas,” Stimpson said. “Please continue to be weather aware as the remnants of Ida move out of our area.”

Because of a state of emergency, scheduled roadside trash collection did not occur today. Trash crews will be starting on Monday’s routes tomorrow and will catch up during the week on all other routes. Crews are expected to be back on a regular trash schedule by the end of this week.

node.text:
City operations will close with the exception of emergency personnel in response to Hurricane Ida. The City of Mobile will designate the Alert status mobilization period for Hurricane Ida as of 12:00 pm Sunday, August 29, 2021, until a time to be determined.  In accordance with this order, City of Mobile offices will be closed Monday, August 30th. During this time period, employees will be paid in accordance with the City of Mobile’s Emergency or Disaster Days Policy. We will continue to monitor the status of the storm and notify employees of any changes.

William S. Stimpson
Mayor

node.text: “ In times of crisis, Mobilians have always rallied together, and now it’s time to rally behind these men and women with our prayers, love and outward support to show our heartfelt appreciation for all they are doing to protect and preserve our health and the lives of many in our City. If your neighbor, friend or family member is a frontline healthcare worker, offer to buy them lunch, or cut their grass or do anything that might help remind them that we still have their back. More importantly, we are asking all citizens to show their support by getting vaccinated, wearing masks, embracing social distance and good hygiene and doing the other things we know reduce the spread of COVID-19.”
